SIMPLE: following
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Following
<hw>Fol"low*ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One's
followers, adherents, or dependents, collectively.</def>
<rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Vocation; business; profession.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Following</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Following
<hw>Fol"low*ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Next after;
succeeding; ensuing; <as>as, the assembly was held on the
<ex>following</ex> day</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>(In the field of a telescope)
In the direction from which stars are apparently moving (in consequence
of the earth's rotation); <as>as, a small star, north <ex>following</ex>
or south <ex>following</ex></as>. In the direction toward which stars
appear to move is called <xex>preceding</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The four principal directions in the field of a
telescope are <xex>north</xex>, <xex>south</xex>, <xex>following</xex>,
<xex>preceding</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Following edge</ent>⟦br⟧
